### Euclidean Distance = Square Distance

```python
 np.linalg.norm(a-b)
```

$𝑛𝑜𝑟𝑚(𝑎)=||a||=\sqrt{∑_{𝑖=1}^𝑛𝑎^2_𝑖}$

##### The dot product between arrays: All the flavors

*𝑎*⃗ ⋅*𝑏*⃗ $ =∑_{𝑖=1}^𝑛𝑎_i𝑏_𝑖$

### Cosine Similarity: Intuition

Cos of the angle between vectors

![image-20220116221842321](C:\Users\calvchen\AppData\Roaming\Typora\typora-user-images\image-20220116221842321.png)

Can be a better proxy of similarity between these vector representations

It also not dependant on the size of the corpuses, not like Euclidean D.

[^WHY?]: Remember that the main advantage of this metric over the Euclidean distance is that it isn't biased by the size difference between the representations.

